


Constellium - Wikipedia





















 






Constellium

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search


Constellium




Traded as
NYSE: CSTM and Euronext Paris


Industry
Aluminium production


Founded
2011


Headquarters
Amsterdam, Netherlands



Key people


Jean-Marc Germain, CEO [1]
Peter Matt, CFO[2]


Website
http://www.constellium.com/


Constellium is a global producer of aluminium semi-products with headquarters in Amsterdam, Netherlands. It was created when Rio Tinto sold off Alcan Engineered Products to Apollo Management (51%) and FSI (10%) in 2011.[3][4] Alcan Engineered Products was the result of various mergers and acquisitions between Pechiney, Alcan and Alusuisse. Constellium is listed on the New York Stock Exchange and Euronext Paris since May 2013.[5]
It has a board of ten directors and maintain a one-tier board of directors consisting of both executive directors and non-executive directors (each a “director”). Under Dutch law, the board of directors is responsible for the policy and day-to-day management. The non-executive directors supervise and provide guidance to the executive directors.[6]
Constellium manufactures aluminium rolled products and extruded products based on a large variety of advanced alloys. It has customers in different industries, including mainly aerospace, automotive and packaging sectors.
Constellium reported €4.7 billion in revenues in 2016.[7]



